# calculate accuracy measures and confusion matrix. Printing the same as heatmap

print("Confusion Matrix")
cm=metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, predicted_labels, labels=['Normal', 'Type_H', 'Type_S'])

df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ['Normal', 'Type_H', 'Type_S']],
                  columns = [i for i in ['Predict Normal', 'Predict Type_H', 'Predict Type_S']])
plt.figure(figsize = (7,5))

In [59]:
# Automating the task of finding best values of K for KNN

scores =[]
for k in range(1,50):
    NNH = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = k, weights = 'distance' )
    NNH.fit(X_train, y_train)
    scores.append(NNH.score(X_test, y_test))
    
plt.plot(range(1,50),scores)

    NNH.fit(X_train, y_train)
    scores.append(NNH.score(X_test, y_test))
    
plt.plot(range(1,5),scores)

It is generally not advisable to create model on non-scaled data in case of KNN. But in this exceptional case, this method is showing better results than the one with scaled data

Conclusion¶

LogisticRegression(solver="liblinear") or LogisticRegression(solver="liblinear", penalty='l1') can be used in this case for getting best results with an accuracy of 95%

Out of these two models, LogisticRegression(solver="liblinear", penalty='l1') is better as it predicts slightly higher number of true positives which is evident in higher recall and f1-score. But one has to also keep in mind that the number of predicted false positives are also marginally higher.
